bug.short_desc: Support queryTimeout in batch writing queries

long_desc.thetext:
Currently when multiple insert/updates in a single transaction are committed a queryTimeout set on the DescriptorQueryManager does not get set on the PreparedStatement that executes all the multiple calls.
A change should be added that will pick up the queryTimeout field set on the queryManager on the descriptor of the root object being registered in the unitOfWork. This global queryTimeout int should be set on the PreparedStatement before committing to the db when in a batch state.

A change to ParameterizedSQLBatchWritingMechanism will be done to link the Statement to the queryManager. statement.setQueryTimeout(lastCallAppended.getQuery().getDescriptor().getQueryManager().getQueryTimeout());
Test: Verify timeout passed to Statement using â€“1 QueryTimeoutBatchPassedToJDBCTest extends QueryTimeoutBatchTestCase A quick way besides using an actual insert/update query of >1 sec would be to use a queryTimeout of negative 1, according to java.sql.Statement.setQueryTimeout() an SQLException will occur for a negative value. This will ensure that the Statement has received the non-default queryTimeout.

Everyone, The following change will be checked into eclipse, any feedback is welcome.
Short Description: -------------------------- Batched query timeout: Add query timeout support for dynamic/parameterized batched inserts/updates. Metadata support for query-timeout exists for both DatabaseQuery and DescriptorQueryManager
